President of the Council ( on. Mr. BROWN), in the course of the debate, said he ho d to see the day when our young men wou d go forth from among us to settle the North-West territory. I harbor no such wish. On the contrary, one of the fondest hopes I cherish as a result of Confederation is, that it will so attract capital and enterprise to the pro- vinces, so tend to develops our internal resources, as to offer to the youth of the country a ﬁeld for the exercise of that laudable energy and ambition which . now cause so many of them to leave their own hearths and cast their lot with strangers. One of the greatest ills that Canada now suffers from is, that the young men born and brought up in her midst look abroad for their future, and bestow their energies and talents on another land; and, although an immigrant myself, I know and admit that a man born and brought up here is worth any two immi- grants for the arduous task of clearing and settling what remains to us of the public domain. It would be unfair, at this late stage of the debate, to enter further into details. I promised that I would not do so. With details, indeed, it has all along appeared to me we had little to do now. If the project as a whole be good, surely means will be found, as .we go on, to remedy objectionable details.
